Reference-contexts: Thus, it is generally agreed that there are still some areas of research in workflow systems. Crucial areas of work include fault tolerance, continuous availability and replication <ref> [MAG + 95] </ref>. In this paper, we will present a distributed work-flow design system that addresses exactly these areas of research and report on the implementation status of our design. <p> Using a browser interface provides a simple, familiar interface which furthers our design goal of providing ease of use. Using a browser interface also allows the user to be mobile. Although this is not one of our primary goals, it is a current topic in workflow research <ref> [MAG + 95] </ref>. Once the Toolflow has been created and started, the Toolflow Monitor will show the user the toolflow's state by showing the Tool Servers in different color according to whether they are in progress, done or not started. <p> Which database engine is used is unimportant; what is relevant about the Database Server in our design is the transaction model that we define. Workflow systems are usually characterized by long-lived transactions and thus a need for advanced 4 transaction models [SSU95] <ref> [MAG + 95] </ref>. One ac-tivity may take many days; perhaps a clerk who is to process an application is on vacation. Our toolflow system is no different. The CAD tools offered by the Tool Servers in a workflow could take hours or days to process the data. <p> We will demonstarte our design at the 1997 Design Automation Conference where we hope to receive a positive reception and thereby motivate outside parties to contribute tools of their own. 7 Limitations in our Design Our toolflow design does not interact with other work-flow systems, functionality that the literature recommends <ref> [MAG + 95] </ref> [AAAM97]. Also, security is an issue as data is possibly flowing through wide-area 7 networks. <p> This all indicates that this is a a very fruitful area of research, especially in light of the new network technologies available, such as Java. 10 Conclusion <ref> [MAG + 95] </ref> cites 6 major workflow areas in need of research: fault tolerance, compensation and navigation, high availability via replication, mobile computing, distributed coordination and advanced transaction models.
